Def for creating functions ex: def *function name*():
adding a variable in the () gives it a condition to be met
  EX: def greet_user(user_name):
    """Display a simple greeting."""
    print(f"Hello, {user_name.title()}!")

greet_user("Corey")

This prints out: Hello, Corey!
However this method requires the user name used or if a second statement is added (see below) then the variable has to match the intended output
EX:print(f"Hello, {user_name.title()}!" 
          f" I see you're from {city.title()}.")
THis can be avoided by specifying or assiging the variable in the function call with the one in the def 
EX: greet_user("Corey", "Seattle")
greet_user(city="Seattle", user_name="Corey")
This will get you the same output even though the variables are swapped in the ()
Another method is to have a preassigned variable
EX: def greet_user(user_name, city, country="USA"):
    """Display a simple greeting."""
    print(f"Hello, {user_name.title()}!" 
          f" I see you're from {city.title()}, {country}.")
With country being defined as USA in the (), it will always be USA in the output. Unless it is defined differently in the function call, as the output below shows
EX: greet_user("Corey", "Seattle")
greet_user(city="Seattle", user_name="Corey")
greet_user("Corey", "Seattle", country="Canada")

Hello, Corey! I see you're from Seattle, USA.
Hello, Corey! I see you're from Seattle, USA.
Hello, Corey! I see you're from Seattle, Canada.

Return is used in a function to return the value that is created from the function
EX:
def get_formatted_name(first_name, last_name):
    """Return a full name, neatly formatted."""
    full_name = f"{first_name} {last_name}"
    return full_name.title()

me = get_formatted_name('saint', 'jackson')
print(me)

This will return Saint Jackson because the variable me uses the get_formatted_name function to use the .title() function on any variables provided for the get_formatted_name function
Line 33-36 defines it, take two variables and assigns them to first_name and last_name then assigns them to full_name, finally return assigns the value as the output for the function while also adding the .title() function to the output as well
in Line 38, me is assigned the get_formatted_name function with the variable provided. With this me gets the output as its assigned variable.

There is also a way to create an if/else within incase a variable needs to be optional
def get_formatted_name(first_name, last_name, middle_name=''):
    """Return a full name, neatly formatted."""
    if middle_name:
        full_name = f"{first_name} {middle_name} {last_name}"
    else:
        full_name = f"{first_name} {last_name}"
    return full_name.title()

me = get_formatted_name('saint', 'jackson', 'michael')
print(me)

me = get_formatted_name('saint', 'jackson')
print(me)   

With this, middle name is the optional and with the if statement, the middle name is added in the middle as defined in Line 49 where as line 57 shows if the middle name isnt defined and instead you get the else defined in line 51. Output below:
