This can be used with a loop to fill a dictonary or list while also asking for input, see below
EX:
def build_person(first_name, last_name, age=None):
    """Return a dictionary of information about a person."""
    person = {'first': first_name, 'last': last_name}
    if age:
        person['age'] = age
    return person

while True:    
    print("\nWhat is your name:")
    print("(enter 'q' to quit)")       
    f_name = input("First name: ")
    if f_name == 'q':
        break
    l_name = input("Last name: ")
    if l_name == 'q':
        break
    age = input("Age (optional): ")
    if age == 'q':
        break
    age = int(age) if age else None

    person = build_person(f_name, l_name, age)
    print(f"\nWelcome, {person['first']} {person['last']}!")

Line 67-72 uses the build_person function to create a dictonary that will take first name, last name, and age(optional). But lines 74-86 are the loop and work outside of the function to get the input using the a new variable that will input. The loop isn't necessary as the value
can be used if the variable names in Line 88 are changed to match the ones used in the function. The multiple if statements used in the loop are to give a break statement as the loop is defined with no way to prove a statement false
